4-Be- 7 LANL EVAL-JUN16 I.Thompson, P.R.Page NDS 148, 1 (2018) DIST-FEB18 ----ENDF/B-VIII.0 MATERIAL 419 -----INCIDENT NEUTRON DATA ------ENDF-6 FORMAT
============================================================ ENDF File Documentation ============================================================
***************************************************************** REACTIONS: 7Be(n,n) (MT=2), 7Be(n,p) (MT=600), 7Be(n,d) (MT=650) and 7Be(n,alpha) (MT=800) calculated from R-matrix analysis of reactions in the 8Be system.
IMPORTANT COMMENTS: The range of the evaluation is for En up to 8.1 MeV. The MT=2 evaluation was obtained without fitting any experimental data on that reaction, although the reaction is constrained by isospin symmetry to 7Li(p,p) and 7Li(p,n), for which substantial data were entered. The MT=600 evaluation was obtained without fitting any experimental data on that reaction (except for a set of very low-energy data discussed below), although the reaction is constrained by time reversal symmetry to 7Li(p,n), for which substantial data were entered. The MT=650 evaluation was obtained without fitting any experimental data on that reaction, although the reaction is constrained by time reversal symmetry to 6Li(d,n), for which substantial data were entered for most of the energy region (except the highest energies), and via isospin symmetry to 6Li(d,p), for which substantial data were entered for the entire energy region. The MT=800 evaluation was obtained without fitting any experimental data on that reaction, although the reaction is constrained by isospin symmetry to 7Li(p,alpha) for which substantial data were entered.
DATA ENTERED: The data entered are discussed in P.R. Page, ``8Be nuclear data evaluation'', LANL Memo T-16:NW-18/6-04. Data for MT=600 (with energy range in eV in brackets) come from Koehler 1988 (0.0253-13530) and Cervena 1989 (0.0253).
*MF=3, MT=2,600,650,800 integrated cross sections: Data for MT=600 are entered from Koehler and Cervena. For MT=800 care was taken to make all data consistent with the convention that the integrated cross section should be divided by a factor of two for identity of the outgoing alpha-particles.
*MF=6, MT=2,600,650,800 angular distributions: Legendre moments calculated from R-matrix analysis. Data that determines moments have not been entered at all.
EXTENSION FROM 8.1 to 20 MeV maximum neutron energy: Cross sections for total, elastic, (n,p) and (n,a) extended to 20 MeV by rescaling the results of a defaults TALYS 1.6 calculation (without pre-equilibrium) to match the previous curves at 8.1 MeV. Ian Thompson. Jun 8, 2016
